You are an expert at trading-card arbitrage data quality. Your task is to improve a Python classifier that decides whether an MYP (Brazilian Pokémon marketplace) → TCGplayer row is a CLEAN deal or a false positive, and if false, which kind. A false "clean" on a flagged row hands the operator a FAKE margin, so precision on the CLEAN class matters most; a missed clean deal forgoes profit.

Hard contract — your program MUST expose exactly:
- `def classify_deal(features: dict) -> str` returning one of: "clean", "supranumerary", "tcg_suspect", "reject"
- a module-level float `MIN_MARGIN` (gross-margin floor, default 0.30)
- a module-level float `SUSPECT_RATIO` (declared_tcg / last_sale suspect cutoff, default 10.0)

`features` keys (all offline-derivable): margin (float, gross fraction), condition (str e.g. "NM"/"SP"), language (str e.g. "EN"/"PT"), card_num (int), set_total (int), declared_tcg (float), last_sale (float | None), rarity (str). Use ONLY the Python standard library — no third-party imports, no network, no import of the MYP scanner package.

Hard invariants you MUST NOT relax:
- NM-only: condition must be exactly Near-Mint ("NM"), matched exactly (uppercase/strip first; substring matching leaks "SP").
- EN-only: language must be English ("EN").
- Margin is GROSS and pure (no embedded fees); reject when margin < MIN_MARGIN.

Known levers (from prior domain knowledge):
- Tune MIN_MARGIN (gross floor; production 0.30) at the borderline margin cases.
- Refine the supranumerary rule (card_num > set_total, e.g. 226/217 → IR/SIR/SAR mislabeled "Comum"); guard unparseable / zero denominators so you don't over-flag.
- Tune SUSPECT_RATIO (declared/last_sale; production 10.0); the suspect check runs only when both declared_tcg and a positive last_sale exist (None last_sale must not crash or false-flag).
- Mind check precedence: REJECT invariants first, then supranumerary, then suspect — a row failing an invariant rejects even if also supranumerary/suspect.
- Optimize CLEAN-class F1 WITHOUT inflating clean by loosening guards (a fake margin is worse than a missed deal).

